<div id="review_80942011" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/80942011" />
    <a title="Asa" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1904061-asa"><img alt="Asa" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/80942011?book_show_action=true">Dec 14, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Asa" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Asa" href="/user/show/1904061-asa">Asa</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9789100563356" href="/book/show/1791884.Juloratoriet">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1904061-asa?shelf=1001-books">1001-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1904061-asa?shelf=annoying_main_character">annoying_main_character</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer80942011&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer80942011" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6213666164734350258">This book started out well, with a man returning to his home town to conduct Bach&apos;s Christmas Oratorio. The story then skips back to show how his grandmother Solveig&apos;s tragic death prevented a performance of this work, and the family&apos;s history after this tragedy. <br/><br/>And then things started to fall apart for me. First Solveig&apos;s husband, Aron, goes crazy with grief, imagines that a woman in New Zeeland that he has started to write to is really Solveig in disguise, and when he realizes, in a moment of</span>
  <span id="freeText6213666164734350258" style="display:none">This book started out well, with a man returning to his home town to conduct Bach's Christmas Oratorio. The story then skips back to show how his grandmother Solveig's tragic death prevented a performance of this work, and the family's history after this tragedy. <br /><br />And then things started to fall apart for me. First Solveig's husband, Aron, goes crazy with grief, imagines that a woman in New Zeeland that he has started to write to is really Solveig in disguise, and when he realizes, in a moment of lucidity, that he has just imagined this he kills himself. Then Solveig's brother, Torin, another socially awkward man, falls to pieces, first because he doesn't get to see his son, and then because he discovers that it wasn't his son, and is only rescued by the stereotypical prostitute with a heart of gold. Sidner, Solveig's son, also feels disconnected from life and goes a bit crazy because he doesn't have a woman in his life that wants him, and the mother of his child isn't interested in him. He travels to New Zeeland to rescue the woman his father abandoned who went crazy afterwards, but feels betrayed when he gets there and she seems to be fine. Luckily for him, she's just faking it and his life's back on track when he gets to take care of her. Finally there's Viktor, Sidner's son and the narrator in the beginning of his book. He blames all the problems in his childhood on his mother, who is a dreamer and encourages this tendency in him as well, which is described as her poisoning him. Then she discovers that he has some talent at painting, and wants him to become a famous painter, which is horrible to Viktor, who is rescued by his father returning after ten years and revealing that he has been writing to Viktor all these years and that his mother has been keeping these letters from him. This allows Viktor to rebel against his mother and stop painting and instead let his father teach him to play the piano, thus leading up to him becoming a conductor instead.<br /><br />I liked the language in the book, and there were some good descriptions of people feeling alienated from life or going slowly crazy, but since it seemed that all the problem that men had were caused by women not being there or not letting the men into their lives I got a bit bored with it. Seriously, once could be interesting, but four times? </span>
  <a data-text-id="6213666164734350258" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


